    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Big Tobacco, Duly Punished?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Raul R Cuadrado letter on July 15 article hails contributions to public health of lawyers, like those in Florida case, who sue tobacco companies</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''High-Flying Lawyer Again Inflicts Damages on Tobacco Industry'' (news article, July 15):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''High-Flying Lawyer Again Inflicts Damages on Tobacco Industry'' (news article, July 15):</p>
        <p>The contribution to public health and medicine made by the lawyers Stanley M. and Susan Rosenblatt, by the victory they obtained against the tobacco companies, have more value for human lives than many public health education programs used for decades against smoking.</p>
        <p>Courageous lawyers in other countries where smoking is highly prevalent must emulate this victory, for it is a public health disgrace to see the bonanza in profits made by the sale of tobacco in places like Japan, China, Europe and South America.</p>
        <p>Sometimes it takes allies in other fields, like law, to accomplish what we in public health and medicine are unable to do by reason and persuasion.</p>
        <p>RAUL R. CUADRADO  Dean, College of Allied Health  Nova-Southeastern University  Fort Lauderdale, Fla., July 16, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
